<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
	ws-function-notation.ptx
	Worksheet 1.1: Review of Multivariable Function Notation.

	Guided-notes mechanisms used in this worksheet:

	1. <fillin characters="N"/>
	   A blank line of width N characters that appears in BOTH builds.
	   Students write in it during class; on the instructor copy it's
	   still a blank, but a <commentary> block immediately below
	   gives the intended answer (see #2).

	2. <commentary><p>...</p></commentary>
	   A block element whose visibility is controlled by the
	   'commentary' stringparam (set per-target in project.ptx).
	   The instructor targets set commentary="yes"; the student
	   targets leave it off, so commentary blocks vanish entirely
	   from student handouts.

	3. <exercise> with <statement> and <solution>
	   For multi-step worked computations.  Visibility is controlled
	   by the publication file's <exercise-worksheet @solution=.../>.
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-function-notation">
	<title>Review: Multivariable Function Notation</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li>Recall the input/output structure of a function and
				the vocabulary of domain and range.</li>
			<li>Distinguish scalar functions of one, two, and three
				variables from one another.</li>
			<li>Preview vector-valued functions, which are the
				central objects of this course.</li>
			<li>Evaluate and find the (natural) domain of a
				multivariable function.</li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 1: The function concept
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>I. What is a function?</alert></p>

		<p>
			A <term>function</term> <m>f</m> takes inputs from a set
			called the <term>domain</term> and produces outputs in
			a set called the <term>range</term> (or codomain).
			Schematically,
			<md>
				f \colon \underbrace{\text{Domain}}_{\text{inputs}}
				\;\longrightarrow\;
				\underbrace{\text{Range}}_{\text{outputs}}.
			</md>
		</p>

		<p>
			The defining properties of a function:
			<ul>
				<li>For each input there is <fillin characters="14"/>
					output.</li>
				<li>Two different inputs <fillin characters="4"/>
					produce the same output.</li>
				<li>One input <fillin characters="12"/> produce two
					different outputs.</li>
			</ul>
		</p>
		<!-- <commentary>
			<p>
				Fill in, in order:
				<q>exactly one</q>,
				<q>can</q>,
				<q>can never</q>.
			</p>
		</commentary> -->

		<p>
			We use the notation <m>f(x)</m>, <m>f(x,y)</m>,
			<m>f(x,y,z)</m>, and (later) <m>\vF(x,y)</m>,
			<m>\vF(x,y,z)</m> depending on what kind of input the
			function takes and what kind of output it produces.
		</p>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 2: Build-up of dimension
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>II. Building up from one variable to many.</alert></p>

		<p>
			<em>In Calculus 1 and 2</em>, you worked with functions
			<m>f(x)</m> of a single variable:
			<ul>
				<li>Input: <m>x \in</m> <fillin characters="3"/>
					<nbsp/>(a real number, i.e., a point on the
					<m>1</m>-dimensional line).</li>
				<li>Output: <m>f(x) \in</m> <fillin characters="3"/>.</li>
				<li>In symbols, <m>f \colon \R \to \R</m>.</li>
			</ul>
		</p>
		<!-- <commentary>
			<p>Both blanks: <m>\R</m>.</p>
		</commentary> -->

		<p>
			<em>In Calculus 3</em>, you met functions of two and
			three variables:
			<ul>
				<li>Input for <m>f(x,y)</m>: <m>(x,y) \in</m>
					<fillin characters="4"/>
					<nbsp/>(a point in the <m>2</m>-dimensional plane).</li>
				<li>Input for <m>f(x,y,z)</m>: <m>(x,y,z) \in</m>
					<fillin characters="4"/>
					<nbsp/>(a point in <m>3</m>-dimensional space).</li>
				<li>Output: still a single real number,
					<m>f(x,y) \in</m> <fillin characters="3"/>
					<nbsp/>or <m>f(x,y,z) \in</m>
					<fillin characters="3"/>.</li>
				<li>In symbols, <m>f \colon \R^2 \to \R</m> or
					<m>f \colon \R^3 \to \R</m>.</li>
			</ul>
		</p>
		<!-- <commentary>
			<p>
				Blanks, in order: <m>\R^2</m>, <m>\R^3</m>, <m>\R</m>,
				<m>\R</m>.
			</p>
		</commentary> -->

		<p>
			<em>In this course</em>, we'll also need
			<term>vector-valued functions</term> <m>\vF(x,y)</m> and
			<m>\vF(x,y,z)</m>:
			<ul>
				<li>Input: a point in <fillin characters="4"/>
					<nbsp/>or <fillin characters="4"/>
					<nbsp/>(same as before).</li>
				<li>Output: a <em>vector</em>, <m>\vF(x,y) \in</m>
					<fillin characters="4"/>
					<nbsp/>or <m>\vF(x,y,z) \in</m>
					<fillin characters="4"/>.</li>
				<li>In symbols, <m>\vF \colon \R^2 \to \R^2</m> or
					<m>\vF \colon \R^3 \to \R^3</m>.</li>
			</ul>
		</p>
		<!-- <commentary>
			<p>
				Blanks, in order: <m>\R^2</m>, <m>\R^3</m>,
				<m>\R^2</m>, <m>\R^3</m>.
			</p>
		</commentary> -->

		<p>
			<alert>Vocabulary.</alert>
			A function whose output is a single real number is
			called a <term>scalar function</term> (or
			<term>scalar field</term>).  A function whose output
			is a vector is called a <term>vector-valued
			function</term> (or <term>vector field</term>).
		</p>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 3: Evaluating scalar functions
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>III. Evaluating scalar functions of several
			variables.</alert></p>

		<p>
			To <term>evaluate</term> a multivariable function at a
			point, substitute the coordinates of the point for the
			variables and simplify &#8212; exactly as you did with
			<m>f(x)</m>, just with more variables.
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ex-eval-fxy">
			<title>Evaluating <m>f(x,y)</m></title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let <m>f(x,y) = x - x\sqrt{y}</m>.  Compute
					<m>f(1,4)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<md>
						<mrow>
							f(1,4) \amp = (1) - (1)\sqrt{4}		</mrow>
						<mrow>
									\amp = 1 - 2 = -1.			  </mrow>
					</md>
					So <m>f(1,4) = -1</m>, which is a scalar &#8212;
					consistent with <m>f \colon \R^2 \to \R</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ex-eval-fxyz">
			<title>Evaluating <m>f(x,y,z)</m></title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Let
					<md>
						g(x,y,z) = \frac{\cos z}{x} - x.
					</md>
					Compute <m>g(-1,\,0,\,\pi)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<md>
						<mrow>
							g(-1,0,\pi) \amp
								= \frac{\cos\pi}{-1} - (-1)		 </mrow>
						<mrow>
									\amp = \frac{-1}{-1} + 1
									= 1 + 1 = 2.					</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p>
			<alert>Your turn.</alert>
			Work each of the following with a neighbor.  Solutions
			appear on the instructor key.
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="exer-eval-practice">
			<title>Evaluation practice</title>
			<task xml:id="task-eval-a">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Let <m>f(x,y) = x^2 - 3xy + y^2</m>.  Find
						<m>f(2,-1)</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>f(2,-1) = 4 - 3(2)(-1) + 1 = 4 + 6 + 1
						= 11</m>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</task>
			<task xml:id="task-eval-b">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Let <m>h(x,y) = \dfrac{x+y}{x-y}</m>.  Find
						<m>h(3,1)</m> and explain why
						<m>h(2,2)</m> is undefined.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>h(3,1) = \dfrac{3+1}{3-1} = \dfrac{4}{2}
						= 2</m>.  For <m>(2,2)</m> the denominator
						is <m>2 - 2 = 0</m>, so the formula is
						undefined there.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</task>
			<task xml:id="task-eval-c">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Let <m>k(x,y,z) = xy + yz + zx</m>.  Find
						<m>k(1,2,3)</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>k(1,2,3) = (1)(2) + (2)(3) + (3)(1)
						= 2 + 6 + 3 = 11</m>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</task>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 4: Domain
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>IV. The (natural) domain of a multivariable
			function.</alert></p>

		<p>
			When a function is given by a formula and the domain is
			not specified, the <term>natural domain</term> is the
			set of all inputs for which the formula yields a real
			number.  The familiar restrictions still apply:
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Cannot divide by <fillin characters="6"/>.</li>
			<li>Cannot take an even root of a
				<fillin characters="9"/> <nbsp/>number.</li>
			<li>Cannot take the logarithm of a
				<fillin characters="14"/> <nbsp/>number.</li>
		</ul>
		<!-- <commentary>
			<p>
				Blanks, in order: <q>zero</q>, <q>negative</q>,
				<q>non-positive</q>.
			</p>
		</commentary> -->

		<exercise xml:id="ex-domain-disk">
			<title>A disk-shaped domain</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the natural domain of
					<md>
						f(x,y) = \sqrt{4 - x^2 - y^2}.
					</md>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					We need <m>4 - x^2 - y^2 \ge 0</m>, equivalently
					<m>x^2 + y^2 \le 4</m>.  So the natural domain
					is the closed disk of radius <m>2</m> centered
					at the origin in <m>\R^2</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="exer-domain-practice">
			<title>Domain practice</title>
			<task xml:id="task-dom-a">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the natural domain of
						<m>g(x,y) = \dfrac{\ln(x+y)}{x-y}</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						The logarithm requires <m>x + y > 0</m>;
						the denominator requires <m>x - y \ne 0</m>,
						i.e., <m>y \ne x</m>.  So
						<md>
							\dom(g) = \{(x,y) \in \R^2
							: x + y > 0 \text{ and } y \ne x\},
						</md>
						the open half-plane above the line
						<m>y = -x</m>, minus the line
						<m>y = x</m>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</task>
			<task xml:id="task-dom-b">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the natural domain of
						<m>h(x,y,z) = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{1 - x^2 - y^2 - z^2}}</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						We need the radicand strictly positive (it
						sits in the denominator):
						<m>1 - x^2 - y^2 - z^2 > 0</m>, i.e.,
						<m>x^2 + y^2 + z^2 &lt; 1</m>.  The natural
						domain is the open unit ball in
						<m>\R^3</m>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</task>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 5: A first look at vector-valued functions
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><alert>V. A first look at vector-valued
			functions.</alert></p>

		<p>
			A vector-valued function in <m>\R^2</m> assigns to each
			input point <m>(x,y)</m> a <em>vector</em> in <m>\R^2</m>,
			for instance
			<md>
				\vF(x,y) = \langle\, x - y,\; x + y \,\rangle
				= (x-y)\,\vi + (x+y)\,\vj.
			</md>
			The two real-valued expressions
			<m>F_1(x,y) = x-y</m> and <m>F_2(x,y) = x+y</m> are
			called the <term>component functions</term> of
			<m>\vF</m>.  Each component is a scalar function of the
			same inputs.
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ex-eval-vf">
			<title>Evaluating a vector-valued function</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					With
					<m>\vF(x,y) = \langle x-y,\, x+y \rangle</m>
					as above, compute <m>\vF(2,3)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<m>\vF(2,3) = \langle 2 - 3,\, 2 + 3 \rangle
					= \langle -1,\, 5 \rangle</m>, a vector in
					<m>\R^2</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="exer-vf-practice">
			<title>Vector-valued evaluation</title>
			<task xml:id="task-vf-a">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Let
						<m>\vG(x,y,z) = \langle xy,\; y - z,\; xz^2 \rangle</m>.
						Compute <m>\vG(2,-1,3)</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow>
								\vG(2,-1,3) \amp
								= \langle (2)(-1),\,
										  (-1)-(3),\,
										  (2)(3)^2 \rangle		   </mrow>
							<mrow>
											\amp
								= \langle -2,\, -4,\, 18 \rangle.	</mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</task>
			<task xml:id="task-vf-b">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Let
						<m>\vF(x,y) = \langle -y,\, x \rangle</m>.
						Compute <m>\vF(1,0)</m>, <m>\vF(0,1)</m>,
						<m>\vF(-1,0)</m>, and <m>\vF(0,-1)</m>.
						Sketch each output vector with its tail at
						the corresponding input point.  What does
						the picture suggest?
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<m>\vF(1,0) = \langle 0,1 \rangle</m>,
						<m>\vF(0,1) = \langle -1,0 \rangle</m>,
						<m>\vF(-1,0) = \langle 0,-1 \rangle</m>,
						<m>\vF(0,-1) = \langle 1,0 \rangle</m>.
						Each output is a <m>90^\circ</m>
						counterclockwise rotation of the input
						position vector; the picture is a
						rotational vector field.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</task>
		</exercise>

		<p>
			<alert>Summary.</alert>
			All of the function notation from this course fits in
			the same pattern: an input from <fillin characters="6"/>
			<nbsp/>and an output in either <fillin characters="3"/>
			<nbsp/>(scalar function) or <fillin characters="6"/>
			<nbsp/>(vector-valued function).  The next worksheet
			zooms in on the structure of those output vectors.
		</p>
		<!-- <commentary>
			<p>
				Blanks, in order: <m>\R^n</m>, <m>\R</m>,
				<m>\R^m</m>.
			</p>
		</commentary> -->
	</page>

</worksheet>
